  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: b492ab769d202ee4183275be4bff9429, type: 3}
  m_Name: The Singing-Woman from the Wood's Edge
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::FlightPaper.ProjectSorrow.Poems.PoemScriptableObject
  id: 54
  title: The Singing-Woman from the Wood's Edge
  author: Edna St. Vincent Millay
  isFemaleAuthor: 1
  stanzas:
  - lines:
    - What should I be but a prophet and a liar,
    - Whose mother was a leprechaun, whose father was a friar?
    - Teethed on a crucifix and cradled under water,
    - What should I be but the fiend's god-daughter?
  - lines:
    - And who should be my playmates but the adder and the frog,
    - That was got beneath a furze-bush and born in a bog?
    - And what should be my singing, that was christened at an altar,
    - But Aves and Credos and Psalms out of the Psalter?
  - lines:
    - You will see such webs on the wet grass, maybe,
    - As a pixie-mother weaves for her baby,
    - You will find such flame at the wave's weedy ebb
    - As flashes in the meshes of a mer-mother's web,
  - lines:
    - But there comes to birth no common spawn
    - From the love of a priest for a leprechaun,
    - And you never have seen and you never will see
    - Such things as the things that swaddled me!
  - lines:
    - After all's said and after all's done,
    - What should I be but a harlot and a nun?
  - lines:
    - In through the bushes, on any foggy day,
    - My Da would come a-swishing of the drops away,
    - With a prayer for my death and a groan for my birth,
    - A-mumbling of his beads for all that he was worth.
  - lines:
    - And there'd sit my Ma, with her knees beneath her chin,
    - A-looking in his face and a-drinking of it in,
    - And a-marking in the moss some funny little saying
    - That would mean just the opposite of all that he was praying!
  - lines:
    - He taught me the holy-talk of Vesper and of Matin,
    - He heard me my Greek and he heard me my Latin,
    - He blessed me and crossed me to keep my soul from evil,
    - And we watched him out of sight, and we conjured up the devil!
  - lines:
    - Oh, the things I haven't seen and the things I haven't known.
    - What with hedges and ditches till after I was grown,
    - And yanked both ways by my mother and my father,
    - With a "Which would you better?" and a "Which would you rather?"
  - lines:
    - With him for a sire and her for a dam,
    - What should I be but just what I am?
  rating: 4
